long-held picture of a medieval Britain lacking in technological sophistication, passively inheriting Roman roads and never engineering any of its own. Previous studies of medieval infrastructure tend to be discipline-specific and technical. This accessible collection draws out the imaginative, symbolic, and cultural significance of the road. The key audience for this book is scholars of medieval Britain (early and late) in all disciplines. Its theoretical foundations will also ensure an audience among scholars of cultural studies, especially those in urban studies, transport studies, and economic history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aRoadszGreat BritainxDesign and constructionxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aRoadszGreat BritainxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aRoman roads.  aScotland.  aWales.  aitineraries.  amedieval literature.  amedieval roads.  anavigable rivers.  anetworks.  apublic works.1 aAllen, Valerie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Valerie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChism, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Ruth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFoster Evans, Dylan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHindle, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Sarah Rees, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLegassie, Shayne Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1